{"Title":"Simple Social Computing Protocol: Signed BSON","Contents":"\n<p><meta charset=\"utf-8\"/>In order to avoid spoofing, and to control SPAM, all server-to-server messages must be cryptographically-signed. SSCP defines&#160;<a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"http://10.0.1.198:1080/Docs/Specs/Simple%20Social%20Computing%20Protocol/signatures.page\">Signed BSON</a>&#160;to do this. Signed BSON is based off of Salmon's&#160;<a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"http://salmon-protocol.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/draft-panzer-magicsig-00.html\">Magic Signatures</a>, which is based off of XML-Dsig, but uses&#160;<a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"http://bsonspec.org/\">Binary JSON</a>&#160;to eliminate ambiguities that arise when trying to sign XML or JSON.</p>"}